built-in-directives/.body:
Built-in Directives
TL;DR

You don&apos;t need to include built-in directives in directives:[]
ngModel has a crazy new syntax: [(ngModel)]=&quot;name&quot;

 Gotchas
In Angular 1, it was confusing when you should use {{}} inside of 
attributes. Angular 2 should consistently always use [] for 
input/setting values and () for output/getting values.
Show Me the Code
NgClass [ngClass]
Used for conditionally applying/removing style classes
import {Component} from &apos;angular2/core&apos;;
@Component({
    selector:&apos;ngclass-example&apos;,
    template: `
    &lt;style&gt;
        .highlight{
            border: 3px solid yellow;
        }

        .selected{
            font-weight: bold;
        }
    &lt;/style&gt;

    &lt;div 
        (mouseover)=&quot;isOver = true&quot; 
        (mouseout)=&quot;isOver = false&quot; 
        (click)=&quot;isSelected = !isSelected&quot;
        [ngClass]=&quot;{highlight: isOver, selected: isSelected}&quot;
        &gt;    
        Roll over me!
    &lt;/div&gt;
`
})
export class NgClassExample{
    isOver = false;
    isSelected = false;
}

NgIf *ngIf
Used for conditionally showing/hiding elements
import {Component} from &apos;angular2/core&apos;;
@Component({
    selector:&apos;ngif-example&apos;,
    template: `
    &lt;button (click)=&quot;isMessageShown = !isMessageShown&quot;&gt;
        {{isMessageShown ? &apos;Hide Message&apos; : &apos;Show Message&apos;}}
    &lt;/button&gt;
    &lt;h1 *ngIf=&quot;isMessageShown&quot;&gt;HI EVERYBODY!!!&lt;/h1&gt;
`
})
export class NgIfExample{
    isMessageShown;
}

NgSwitch [ngSwitch], NgSwitchWhen *ngSwitchWhen, NgSwitchDefault *ngSwitchDefault
Just like a JavaScript switch. Takes a value and returns the matched
case:
import {Component} from &apos;angular2/core&apos;;
@Component({
    selector: &apos;ngswitch-example&apos;,
    template: `
&lt;div&gt;
    &lt;input #i (change)=&quot;num = convertToNumber(i.value)&quot; type=&quot;number&quot; value=&quot;0&quot;&gt;

    &lt;div [ngSwitch]=&quot;num&quot;&gt;
        &lt;p *ngSwitchDefault&gt;Change the number above, I dare you!&lt;/p&gt;
        &lt;p *ngSwitchWhen=&quot;1&quot;&gt;One is the loneliest number&lt;/p&gt;
        &lt;p *ngSwitchWhen=&quot;2&quot;&gt;Two is company&lt;/p&gt;
        &lt;p *ngSwitchWhen=&quot;3&quot;&gt;Three is a crowd&lt;/p&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
`
})
export class NgSwitchExample {
    num = 0;
    convertToNumber = string =&gt; parseInt(string);
}

 Will very so be updated from ngSwitchWhen to ngSwitchCase
NgModel [(ngModel)]
import {Component} from &apos;angular2/core&apos;;
@Component({
    selector: &apos;ngmodel-example&apos;,
    template: `
&lt;div&gt;
    &lt;input type=&quot;text&quot; [(ngModel)]=&quot;name&quot;&gt;
    {{name}}
&lt;/div&gt;
`
})
export class NgModelExample {}

NgFor, NgForm
These are disussed later, but also don&apos;t need to be included.
What&apos;s That Syntax?
[] on Switch and * on Case
The [] is the value being set, the * is the template being used.
[(ngModel)]=&quot;name&quot;
The [()] reprensents an input [] and an output () combined into
one. So an ngModel &quot;sets&quot; and &quot;gets&quot; the value.

events-and-refs/.body:
Events and Refs
TL;DR

Use (click)=&quot;onClick($event)&quot; to handle events in templates
Use (keyup.enter)=&quot;onEnter($event) to handle key events
Use &lt;input #myInput&gt; to reference elements in the template

Handling Events
Events are part of every application. Your user is going to click, type,
resize, etc, etc, so you&apos;d better know how to accomodate them !
Events are handled by wrapping the event name inside of (). So if you
want to handle a click on a button, you type:
&lt;button (click)&gt;

You add a &quot;handler&quot; for the event by assigning it a handler you&apos;ve
defined in your component:

In your template

&lt;button (click)=&quot;onClick()&quot;&gt;Click Me!&lt;/button&gt;


In your Component

onClick(){
    console.log(&apos;clicked!&apos;);
}

The $event Object
To pass along the actual event, use $event in the handler

In your template

&lt;button (click)=&quot;onClick($event)&quot;&gt;Click Me!&lt;/button&gt;


In your Component

onClick(event){
    console.log(event);
}

Keyboard Events
Want to know when a specific key was pressed? Check this out!
  &lt;input
   (keyup.enter)=&quot;onEnter($event)&quot;
   (keyup.esc)=&quot;onEscape($event)&quot;
   (keyup.control.a)=&quot;onControlA($event)&quot;
   (keyup.control.shift.l)=&quot;onControlShiftL($event)&quot;
   &gt;

Add the keyboard combo using the syntax above will allow you filter out
to only the specific keyboard event you want!:tada:
Refs
You can reference values from elements in your template with a ref.
You create a ref using # and a name on any element:
&lt;input #example&gt;


Elsewhere in the same template

{{example.value}}

 Events Required for Changes!
The above example will not automatically update! You need to have
some sort of event firing for it to catch the update. Something as
simple as adding a (keyup) will do the trick:
&lt;input #example (keyup)=&quot;noop&quot;&gt;

Obviously, the above could be handled better with [(ngModel)]
(discussed later), but it&apos;s definitely good to know!
Passing #ref Values to Event Handlers
You can also grab that value off of the input and pass it along to a 
(click) handler:
&lt;input #example&gt;
&lt;button (click)=&quot;onClick(example.value)&quot;&gt;Click Me!&lt;/button&gt;

Show Me the Code

src/components/example.component.ts

import {Component} from &apos;angular2/core&apos;;

@Component({
    selector: &apos;example&apos;,
    template: `
            &lt;input #myInput type=&quot;text&quot;&gt;
            &lt;button (click)=&quot;onClick(myInput.value)&quot;&gt;Show Input Value&lt;/button&gt;
        `
})
export class Example{
    onClick(value){
        console.log(value);
    }
}


src/app.ts

import {Component} from &apos;angular2/core&apos;;
import {Example} from &apos;./components/example.component&apos;;

@Component({
    selector: &apos;app&apos;,
    directives:[Example],
    template: `
        &lt;example&gt;&lt;/example&gt;
    `
})
export class App{
}

What&apos;s That Syntax?
(click)
The () around and event name in a template indicate an Angular 2 event handler.
The #
The # marks an element to be looked up by other elements. Any value
off of the element is available. You can even invoke methods on the
element! Look how the following example focuses on the input when you
click the button:
&lt;input #example&gt;
&lt;button (click)=&quot;example.focus()&quot;&gt;Focus the Example Input&lt;/button&gt;

