@Injectable()
The @Injectable() decorator is required so that Angular 2 has the 
proper Metadata to be able to properly register your service with the 
Injector. You don&apos;t need to worry about the metadata, it&apos;s handled
during compilation from TypeScript to JavaScript. (This is also why 
&quot;emitDecoratorMetadata&quot;: true, is required in your tsconfig.json 
when compiling down your TypeScript.)
Importing vs. Injecting
It&apos;s easy to get confused between import and Injecting, but they&apos;re
not at all the same thing.
Importing (using the import keyword) is simply how JavaScript shares
code across files.
Injecting happens during &quot;runtime&quot; (when your application is running 
in the browser) and is how you share values/instances across your 
application.
What&apos;s That Syntax?
constructor(public foo)
Using public before the foo parameter is syntax sugar for property
assignment.
The following two examples are exactly the same:
class Example{
    foo;

    constructor(foo){
        this.foo = foo;
    }
}

class Example{
    constructor(public foo){
    }
}

So using public saves you a few keystrokes.
constructor(foo:Bar)
Bar is a Type. During compilation, TypeScript will take the metadata from that
Type then the Injector can look it up so it can find the matching value/class 
to provide into the constructor. This requires emitDecoratorMetadata to be
set in your .tsconfig.json.
An altenate approach is to use constructor(@Inject(Bar) foo) where you rely on the
@Inject() decorator to provide the proper values.
Both of the following examples achieve the same result:
Injection using Type
constructor(foo:Bar)
Injection using @Inject()
constructor(@Inject(Bar) foo)

