smart-and-dumb-components/.body:
Smart and Dumb Components
TL;DR
Smart Components

Specific to your App
Are Containers for Dumb Components
Handle passing Data around (covered later)
Handle routing (covered later)
Use providers:[]

Dumb Components

Are reusable across apps
Use @Input() to receive data from the container
@Input() foo; is handled by [foo]=&quot;bar&quot; in the container 
Use @Output() to push data out to the container
@Output() is a new EventEmitter which emit() data out
@Output() foo = new EventEmitter(); is triggered with foo.emit() 
then handled by (foo)=&quot;onFoo()&quot; in the container

Smart Components
There&apos;s only one Component, but some Components are
specific to your application while others are going to be reusable.
We&apos;ll call a Component that&apos;s specific to your application a
&quot;smart&quot; component. This means that your routes, data, and application
wiring would all hook together using these types of Component. In
practice, this means that &quot;smart&quot; Component use providers:[] for
hooking up your application into the Component. 
These Components also load in &quot;dumb&quot; Components, so their templates will
typically be larger and have a few &quot;dumb&quot; components listed in their
directives array.
Dumb Components
A reusable Component is a &quot;dumb&quot; Component. This Component shouldn&apos;t 
know anything about your application. No routes. No services. Nothing 
application specific.
All data in dumb Components should be passed in through @Input(). All
data going out should be pushed out with @Output(). Using providers:[]
in &quot;dumb&quot; components is rare and never used for application data.
